'''Matsuo Shrine''' (まつのおじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Asahicho, {{ill|lt=Kameoka City|Q633996|qid=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|qid=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of shrine rankings|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was classified as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined Deities ===
* '''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōyamagui no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}''' (おおやまぐいのみこと)
* '''{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ichikishimahime no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}''' (いちきしまひめのみこと)

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it is said to have been founded during the {{ill|lt=Wadō era|Q1373026|qid=Q1373026|1=Wadō (era)}} ({{ill|lt=708|Q23511|qid=Q23511|1=708}}–{{ill|lt=715|Q23528|qid=Q23528|1=715}}), when {{ill|lt=Hata no Kawakatsu|Q5680877|qid=Q5680877|lt=Hata no Kawakatsu|1=Hata no Kawakatsu}} enshrined the deities by order of {{ill|lt=Prince Shōtoku|Q263972|qid=Q263972|1=Prince Shōtoku}}. In the *{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}* {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Register of Deities|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it is listed as “Matsuo Shrine” in {{ill|lt=Tanba Province|Q954511|qid=Q954511|1=Tanba Province}} {{ill|lt=Kuwata District|Q11537600|qid=Q11537600|1=Kuwada district}}, and is ranked as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.

It is said to have been revered as the tutelary shrine of nearby villages, but during the {{ill|lt=Tenshō era|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} ({{ill|lt=1573|Q6678|qid=Q6678|1=1573}}–{{ill|lt=1592|Q6769|qid=Q6769|1=1592}}), many shrine buildings were destroyed by fire during the Tanba campaign of {{ill|lt=Akechi Mitsuhide|Q313320|qid=Q313320|1=Akechi Mitsuhide}}, with only the main hall escaping destruction.

=== Shrine Grounds ===
[[File:Matsuo-jinja (Kameoka) otaki.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Otaki]]
The shrine grounds are located at the foot of Mount Saburōgatake on the eastern side of the {{ill|lt=Kameoka Basin|Q11181997|qid=Q11181997|1=Kameoka Basin}}, and have been selected as one of the “100 Natural Sites of Kameoka.”<ref>[http://www.city.kameoka.kyoto.jp/kankyouhozen/kurashi/kurashi/shizen/100sen/083.html 100 Natural Sites of Kameoka: Matsuo Shrine (Kameoka City website)].</ref>

The main hall was constructed in the 7th year of {{ill|lt=Meiō era|Q1193841|qid=Q1193841|1=Meiō}} ({{ill|lt=1498|Q6705|qid=Q6705|1=1498}}) during the {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|qid=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. It is a one-bay {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|qid=Q210684|lt=one-bay nagare-zukuri|1=Nagare-zukuri}} structure with a {{ill|lt=hiwada-buki|Q90373477|qid=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}} roof, and currently stands inside a protective shelter. This main hall is registered as a cultural property by Kyoto Prefecture. In addition, the water used for purification located on the lower level beneath the main hall is spring water flowing from Mount Saburōgatake, known as “Otaki,” and is said never to have dried up even during severe droughts.

